  "notes": [
    "All transfer applicants must meet the University of California admissions eligibility requirements and the campus’s admission selection criteria. All requirements must be completed by the end of the spring term prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility and admission to UC Santa Cruz, visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that guarantees your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "THIS IS A SCREENING MAJOR. Screening majors require completion of specific preparatory coursework and/or a minimum GPA. For details on the specific screening requirements for this major, refer to the \" Transfer Admission Screening Policy \" below. Additional coursework listed under \"Recommended Preparation\" is not required for admission but is strongly recommended to support timely degree completion. For more information, including a list of screening majors and non-screening majors , visit the UCSC Admissions website.",
    "Some Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate Higher Level (IBH), and Advanced Level (A-level) exams satisfy UCSC course requirements. UCSC's exam credit policies may be found on the Degree Progress Unit website .",
    "Biochemistry and Molecular Biology B.S. Transfer Admission Screening Policy Transfer students must complete the following courses, or their articulated equivalents, with a grade of C (2.0) or better in each course, and a cumulative GPA of 2.50 or higher in all required screening courses, by the end of the spring term prior to transferring in the fall: General Chemistry series CHEM 8A – Organic Chemistry CHEM 8B – Organic Chemistry BIOL 20A – Cell and Molecular Biology MATH 11A – Calculus with Applications OR MATH 19A – Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics Refer to the \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" section below for lists of courses approved to fulfill these requirements. It is strongly recommended that community college students complete all required General Chemistry coursework for their intended major at one institution prior to transfer to UC Santa Cruz. Strongly Recommended Major Preparation In addition to the required courses listed above, transfer students are strongly advised to complete the courses listed in the \"Recommended Preparation\" section below. These courses are prerequisites for upper-division courses required for the major. Students who do not complete these preparatory courses before transferring will likely need additional quarters of enrollment to complete their degree. Additional Information for Transfer Prospective transfer students should prioritize required and recommended major preparation courses, and may additionally complete courses that satisfy UC Santa Cruz general education requirements as time allows. For information on incorporating general education requirements into your pre-transfer academic plan, consult with your community college counselor. Please visit the Chemistry & Biochemistry website to learn more about this major. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Biochemistry and Molecular Biology B.S. Program Statement"
